7.2 ALE constitutive equations

Compared to the use of the ALE description in ﬂuid dynamics, the main additional difﬁculty in nonlinear solid mechanics is the design of an appropriate stress-update procedure to deal with history-dependent constitutive equations. As already mentioned, constitutive equations of ALE nonlinear solid mechanics contain convective terms that account for the relative motion between mesh and material. This is the case for both hypoelastoplastic and hyperelastoplastic models.

7.2.1 Constitutive equations for ALE hypoelastoplasticity

Hypoelastoplastic models are based on an additive decomposition of the stretching tensor ∇sv (symmetric part of the velocity gradient) into elastic and plastic parts; see, for instance, Belytschko et al. (2000) or Bonet and Wood (1997). They were used in the ﬁrst ALE formulations for solid mechanics and are still the standard choice. In these models, material behavior is described by a rate-form constitutive equation

